[5] India (Karnataka)
Date: Thu, 16 Oct 2003 11:59:42 +0100
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@derwent.co.uk>
Source: NDTV.com [edited]
<http://www.ndtv.com/template/template.asp?template=Health&slug=Rise+in+dengue+cases+in+Karnataka&id=43772&callid=1&category=National>


Nearly 1000 people have been diagnosed with dengue fever in Karnataka
[so far in 2003] and 7 deaths have been reported.

The monsoon has brought the usual spurt in cases, with mosquitoes
that spread the disease breeding in stagnant water. Doctors say there
has been a clear increase in the number of cases admitted to
hospitals in Bangalore this year. The monsoon related increase in
dengue cases should have ended by now, but 197 cases have been
reported in the state in the last month alone. "Definitely this year
there has been a steady increase, and as far as intensive care is
concerned, we really haven't had a respite at all in the last 4
months," says Dr Jose Chacko, Manipal Hospital.

--
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

******
[6] India (Uttar Pradesh)
Date: Tue, 14 Oct 2003 09:32:39 -0300
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Times of India 14 Oct 2003 [edited]
<http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/>


Kanpur
--------
4 more suspected cases of dengue were reported from Gujaini. The
patients were taken to the UHM and LLR hospitals.

Due to the rising incidence of dengue, special arrangements have been
made at the LLR Hospital. Principal Dr SK Katiyar said that 4 beds in
the medicine department would be kept solely for dengue patients
beginning Monday. Tests for platelet counts of suspected patients
would be done free of cost at the LLR pathology lab.

--
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>


Lucknow
-----------
While 2 cases of dengue fever have been reportedly admitted in
Chhattrapati Shahuji Maharaj Medical University (CSMMU), 4 cases of
Patients with dengue-like symptoms have been reported from SGPGIMS.

Sources at the SGPGIMS also revealed that a severe case of dengue
fever had been referred to the institute from a private hospital, but
the patient was sent to CSMMU as [it] was severe and SGPGIMS has no
speciality facilities for treating dengue. One patient from
Kailashpuri and 2 from Hussainganj were admitted in CSMMU.

At the SGPGIMS, 4 people have been reported with symptoms [resembling
those of] dengue.

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

